          "body": "Jeremiah 30-33 stands as a four-chapter island of promise in a book otherwise dominated by judgment. After twenty-nine chapters indicting Judah for covenant treason and announcing Babylon's coming sword, Yahweh tells Jeremiah to *write all the words I have spoken to you in a book* (30:2) — a fresh literary unit. Chapters 30-31 form the lyric core (oracles of restoration), chapter 32 the historical embodiment (Jeremiah buys a field in Anathoth as exile descends), chapter 33 the priestly-Davidic capstone. Within this 'Book of Consolation,' chapter 31 is the gravitational center, and within chapter 31, vv. 31-34 are the New Testament's most-quoted Old Testament passage. Reading this chapter is reading the architectural plan of the gospel."
